RELEARNING PYTHON

11/10/25 (DAY 1)

THE MOST BASIC:
Variable - Stores information
print() - prints out what is put inside the parenthesis even if its strings, intergers and floats
len() - counts how long a text and other types
#text here# - comment in a code, the code ignores this as its used to organize the code
LEN RULES
[0] - prints the first letter in the variable your referring to
[0:3] - prints the first 3 letters in the variable your referring to
TYPES:
strings - basically texts and when multiplying it prints it multiple times not like numbers
integers - whole numbers, you can multiply subtract and etc
float - numbers with decimals where like integer you can multiply subtract and etc
booleans - True or False
STRINGS RULES
\ - helps with confusion in codes for example print("hello \"world") if we want to add the one parenthesis inside the string we have to add this symbol
\n - basically it cuts the string wherever you put it and put the rest in the next line for example print("hello \nworld") this code would print hello in the first line in the console and print world in the second line
f"" - formatted strings can help print multiple types at once for example print(f"{ex_1} {ex_2}") it will print two of this variables. it can also do integers and other types
NUMBERS RULES AND FUNCTIONS
round() - rounds a decimal number to where its closest to, for example 2.9 would be rounded up to 3 because its closest to the number 3 but if its 2.4 it will stay the same as 2
abs() - basically means ABSOLUTE which returns the absolute of the number where, when a number of negative it will turn them to positive
EXPRESSIONS
+ - additions
- - subtraction
* - multiplication
/ - division
// - basically print out a whole number of a division, theres no decimals
% - prints out the remainder of the division
** - exponent, raised to the power of

FUNCTION = METHODS
.upper() - uppercase every thing in a string or text, for example print(ex_1.upper()) where it will basically change the string words to upper case keep in mind it only works in strings, it will return an attribute error if you try to upper an integers
.lower() - the opposite of upper instead it turns the string to lowercase letters
.title() - it will turn the first letter of a word to an uppercase letter
.strip() - removes the white space at the beginning of the text
.rstrip() - the same function as .strip() but instead it removes the whitespace at the end of the line
.find() - finds the index or in the long version means it will count how many letters it is till you get to the word in the parenthesis keep in mind the word has to be exact as an uppercase is different from a lowercase in the mind of a computer
.replace() - straight forward enough, it just replace the letters you put inside the parenthesis and change the letter that it finds to a specific letter that you put, for example; print(ex_1.replace("a", "o")) it will replace every "a" in the ex_1 variable to "o"
in - basically checks if the letter you put before it is in the variable you put beside it via boolean(True or False), for example; print("Niko" in ex_1) it will look for the word Niko in the variable and if it finds one it will print True and if it doesnt it prints False
not in - basically the same as in but instead of checking if there is one it will check if there no specific word in that variable, for example; print("Niko" not in ex_1) so if it didnt find any it will print out True and if it found one its False

